<br>
You realize the 1000 pt nuke you just outlined is bigger than our biggest lure? In fact your entire line of stone spells demonstrates (imo) a huge overestimation of lures.<br>
<br>
at 44 we can lure for 360ish<br>
at 51 our lure is in the 640 range<br>
by 60 it's 825<br>
<br>
If you wanted 'stone' to fall in line (~70% of wizard nuke) you would have to cut all of your numbers flat in half.<br>
<br>
Admittedly, maybe you are already factoring that in thru armor class... but the numbers you put up, if you actually got those numbers they'd be stomping our toes clean off =)<br>
<br>
As an aside, your stone series would amount to &gt;&gt; lure in pvp, particularly against casters since you'd have a good chance to land a full hit (1hb) and, by the mechanics of it, probably no 60% nerf. From what I've heard, mage versus wiz pvp is one of the few encounters in the game that approaches balance. This would **** it up right squarely =)<br>
<br>
And as Grim said, you already get pets. The only reason we get lures is because we have no pets. I really appreciate your respectful attitude, and I hate to dissagree with ya, but I don't think mages should be any more damaging than they already are. Look, there's already hideous class competition in the damage department. Mages are one of the FEW classes that can potentially get away from that, because you have a monopoly on a utility function (summoning). If verant would make more summoned items that were worth a darn, then mages would fall into favor without stepping on <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> anybody's</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> toes. Mages are the only class I can think of with that type of potential; every other class shares key functions with somebody else, and can't be tweaked without multiple levels of balance issues.<br>
<br>
What I would love -so- much more is if verant fixed pets and made more useful mage-summoned items available. Regarding pets, fixing the pathing would be nice, but even a quick hack to make the indiff to all would help a ton, right? It could be implimented as an alt skill or an enchanter buff if Verant wants to be particularly mean about it =/<br>
<br>
Regarding summoned items: You know what I want to see? Bet you can guess =)  --Summoned items with hideous big +mana!<br>
Maybe a summoned halo with like 400 +mana; rings, earrings, etc...<br>
Speaking of which, I'm still waiting for them to design a Tinkered: mana capacitor (back slot, backpack graphic) with like 500 mana, 15 weight and no other stats.<br>
<br>
And there is supposedly a &quot;summon peridots&quot; spell in the spdat now. If it isn't a mage spell, it damn well should be! Sure, it would require a few lines of hard-code, to make the summoned pdots no-rent (unsellable) but still work as reagents... but it would be so awesome! I suspect this spell would put the epic pet to shame, in terms of influencing group/raid desirability. And again, without stepping on <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> anybody's</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> toes. Indeed without really changing the balance of the game at all!<br>
<br>
How about a mage-summoned sword that procs a HUGE debuff to charisma? ie, the ultimate taunt sword?<br>
<br>
Now it's time for me to completely depart from the realm of the reasonable and dream a bit =)  no need for flames from anyone; I realize the following examples are probably bad ideas, but the mechanics of them might be used for something cool.<br>
...<br>
How about this for a mana-booster item/spell:<br>
mage spell (1.5k mana) summons a no rent item.<br>
<br>
the item is given to others on his raid; it has one charge with a 2 minute cast time to summon a second item, which is the actual mana booster. The mana booster is no drop, and has an instant 1k mana charge on it.<br>
<br>
The point of going thru 2 steps, is that it gives you a huge mana boost item which is tradeable but cannot be stockpiled. (the person recieving the item is forced to stop and cast for 2 minutes before the effect becomes available; after which the effect is instantly available at any time, but no longer tradeable) It would essentially allow the mage to give each person in his group/raid a 1k mana emergency pack.<br>
<br>
You could also design a similar non-stockpilable summons spell to summon a strong arrow (max arrow damage stat x1.5 or something). It would essentially allow a mage to give a single powerful nuke to each of his archers on a raid.<br>
<br>
It would be an awesome item to have, but it would probably unbalance high level encounters, and be no fun for the mage anyway... Summoning a bunch of mana expensive items at the beginning of a raid... yay. bet you gotta hate that... but... You are a summoning class. I have a gut feeling that the majority of your work will always need to come be before the fight starts. There may simply be no way around it.<br>
<br>
Sorry, I know that was a bunch of rambling on my part...<br>
But in short, please don't compete for damage. You're already pretty good at it; the best in some situations; and seeing as damage is a widely-competed racket, you are bound to get people riled up if you push for more. Mages have the potential to be a utility class which is valuable in its own right, without competing with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> anybody</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. That is a rare option, and I wish for your sake and for mine that verant lets you expand in that direction rather than choking the damage field any further. With the utility potential mages have, imo it would be a crying shame and a horrible waste if you were balanced by DD capacity instead. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugrimstafftheurgist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimstaff Theurgist</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/grimicon.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<BR>(Title left blank)</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/10/02 6:50:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=676.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> still no lures</span><hr size=1> The answer is to make your pets more useful in areas where people don't want them now, NOT to give you Lures.  You already have the tools you need, they just aren't allowed by some groups and aren't feasible or safe in some areas.  If Verant fixed those aspects, then nothing would need to be added in terms of Lures.  That's where your fight should be focussed. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usilverbladetheenchanter.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Silverblade the Enchanter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler<